# .cursorrules — "The Best Man" (Cognee Hackathon: Where's My Context?)

## What this project is
"The Best Man" is a decision-memory agent for codebases. It ingests git commits,
PR descriptions/comments, and manually logged decisions into Cognee's knowledge
graph, then answers natural-language questions like "why did we drop approach X?"
by tracing the graph instead of doing flat vector search. It demonstrates the full
Cognee memory lifecycle: remember -> recall -> improve -> forget.

Stack: FastAPI backend, Cognee for memory, React (Vite) frontend, GitHub REST API
for ingestion, SQLite/local files for any non-Cognee bookkeeping needed.

## Non-negotiable ground rules

1. Never invent a Cognee API. The real surface (confirmed against the live
   GitHub repo and docs in 2026) is:
   - High-level: `cognee.remember(data, session_id=None)`,
     `cognee.recall(query, session_id=None)`, `cognee.improve(...)`,
     `cognee.forget(dataset=None, session_id=None)`
   - Low-level/legacy (still supported, use these if high-level calls misbehave
     or you need fine control): `cognee.add(data, dataset_name=...)`,
     `cognee.cognify(datasets=[...])`, `cognee.search(query_text=..., query_type=...)`,
     `cognee.memify(...)`, `cognee.prune.prune_data()`, `cognee.prune.prune_system(metadata=True)`
   - If you are not 100% sure a parameter or function exists, say so out loud in
     the response and check `pip show cognee`'s installed version / the
     installed package source (`site-packages/cognee/__init__.py`) before
     writing code that depends on it. Do not silently guess and move on.

2. Never hardcode secrets. `LLM_API_KEY`, `GITHUB_TOKEN`, and any DB credentials
   live in `.env`, loaded via `python-dotenv` or `pydantic-settings`. `.env` is
   gitignored. Always provide an updated `.env.example` when you add a new
   required variable.

3. All Cognee calls are async. Never wrap them in sync code without `asyncio.run`
   or a proper async route handler. FastAPI route handlers that touch Cognee must
   be declared `async def`.

4. Dataset and session naming is intentional, not arbitrary:
   - One Cognee dataset per ingested repo: `dataset_name=f"repo:{owner}/{repo}"`
   - Manual decision-log entries go into the same dataset, not a separate one,
     so graph traversal can connect them to commits/PRs.
   - Use `session_id` only for ephemeral per-conversation context (e.g. a single
     Q&A turn doing follow-up clarification), never for data meant to persist.

5. Every ingestion function must be idempotent. Re-running ingestion on a repo
   that was already ingested should not duplicate nodes. Check Cognee's
   deduplication behavior (content hashing) before adding custom dedup logic;
   only add your own dedup key (e.g. commit SHA) if Cognee's default hashing
   doesn't cover the case (e.g. the same commit message text appearing in two
   different repos).

6. Known pitfall — do not waste time rediscovering it: on some local setups,
   `cognee.add()` / `cognee.cognify()` can hang indefinitely against local
   OpenAI-compatible LLM endpoints (e.g. Ollama) due to a connectivity test
   that assumes `sk-`-prefixed keys. If running against a local LLM, set a
   non-`sk-` placeholder key only if explicitly configured for a custom
   provider, and add an explicit timeout / health-check step in setup code
   rather than letting it hang silently. Default to a hosted LLM provider
   (e.g. OpenAI) for the hackathon build unless told otherwise — it's the
   path of least friction for a multi-day solo build.

7. Graph traversal visualization is a first-class feature, not a nice-to-have.
   Any `recall()` result shown in the UI should be accompanied by the
   underlying nodes/edges used to answer it, where Cognee's response exposes
   them. If Cognee's response doesn't include traversal metadata, fetch it via
   `cognee.search()` with the appropriate graph search type, or via the
   visualization endpoint, rather than fabricating a plausible-looking path.

8. Never fabricate demo data to look more impressive. The repo used for ingestion
   and the demo must be real (a real GitHub repo Venkat owns or has access to,
   e.g. MemoryWeave or FutureStack). Synthetic/manual decision-log entries used
   in the demo must be clearly real entries the user wrote, not auto-generated
   filler designed to make the graph traversal look good.

## Code style

- Python: type-annotated where practical, `ruff format` + `ruff check` clean,
  100-char line length (matches Cognee's own repo convention). Use
  `cognee.shared.logging_utils`-style structured logging conventions in spirit
  (i.e. structured log lines, not bare `print()`) for anything beyond throwaway
  scripts.
- Prefer explicit, typed Pydantic models for all FastAPI request/response bodies.
  No bare `dict` payloads for any endpoint that's part of the public API surface.
- React: functional components + hooks only. No class components. Keep state
  management simple (useState/useReducer/context) — this is a hackathon project,
  not a Redux showcase.
- No dashes or em-dashes in generated report/documentation prose unless
  grammatically unavoidable; use plain sentence structure instead (matches
  Venkat's existing documentation preference).
- Comments should explain *why*, not *what* — especially around any Cognee
  call where the choice of dataset/session/search-type matters.

## Testing expectations

- Every ingestion function (git commits, PR comments, manual decision log) gets
  a unit test with a mocked GitHub API response and a mocked Cognee client.
  Never let tests make real network calls to GitHub or burn real LLM API credits.
- Integration tests that do exercise real Cognee calls are isolated behind a
  pytest marker (e.g. `@pytest.mark.live_cognee`) and skipped by default in CI;
  document how to run them locally with real credentials.
- Any bug fix must come with a regression test that fails before the fix and
  passes after.
- Run `pytest` and `ruff check` before considering any task complete. State the
  actual command output, don't assume it passed.

## Documentation expectations

- `README.md` stays current with: setup steps, environment variables required,
  how to run the ingestion pipeline, how to run the API, how to run the frontend,
  and how to run tests. If a prompt changes any of these, update the README in
  the same response, don't defer it.
- Maintain `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` describing the ingestion -> graph -> recall
  flow and how `remember/recall/improve/forget` map to the four UI actions in
  the demo.
- Maintain `docs/DEMO_SCRIPT.md` with the exact sequence of actions for the
  hackathon demo video, kept in sync with whatever the UI actually does (don't
  let the script describe features that no longer exist).
- Every new public function gets a docstring with a one-line summary, Args,
  Returns, and a usage example, mirroring the style Cognee itself uses for its
  own public API.

## Workflow expectations for Cursor/Claude when working in this repo

- Before writing code that calls a Cognee function you haven't used yet in this
  project, check the installed Cognee version's actual signature rather than
  assuming from memory or from the marketing site.
- When a prompt asks for a new feature, implement it, write/update its tests,
  and update relevant docs in the same pass — don't split "build it" and
  "document it" into separate untracked steps.
- When something is ambiguous (e.g. which repo to ingest, which search type to
  use for a given question), ask rather than silently picking a default,
  consistent with how Venkat prefers to work.
- Don't introduce new dependencies (databases, queues, frontend libraries)
  without flagging it first — this is a solo, multi-day build, and scope creep
  is the main risk to finishing.
